content: Excellent app. Very stable. Mimics a Mackie Control and then some. The documentation is very thorough but is very technical. It assumes the user already has a large amount of knowledge not just of midi and music production but also of computers and networking. UPDATE. After months of use app stopped connecting. Don't know if it's RTP or the app but since the app requires RTP it doesn't matter. I'm switching to something stable. Pity. It had worked great.

I'm not a production engineer so there are buttons I have no idea what they do. But the ability to use sliders and panpots without a mouse is exactly what I want. Apps are notorious for not providing in depth tutorials and unless someone knows different this app is no different.

Modudulator wheel like button cauz They are detect touch ,where ever i touch them and moves there, unlike vertical sliders which only detect touch on specific areas. Its for velocity control.

I stumbled across this app looking for a simple controller that would allow me to record modulation (as opposed to drawing them in my DAW).  My keyboard is a midi digital piano with no physical controller.  TouchDAW certainly exceeded my expectations.  In addition to recording controller changes, I discovered the X-Y pad works really well with Melt (VSTi).  As others have reported, using MidiHub is much easier than rptMidi and required no configuration.  Of course, this may depend on your setup, but I installed MidiHub without having to open it..  Finally, except for the X-Y pad (which may require some investigation) I do get 2-way feedback on the sliders.  Meaning I can use my phone as a controller and see the change in my DAW and vice versa.  I'm using Cubase 9.5 Pro on WIndows 10 Pro with a Samsung Galaxy S8.

TouchDAW's MIDI utils are very cool and the "crosswire" feature is a hidden gem that allows wireless MIDI from a h/w device like a USB keyboard connected to the tablet/phone  running TouchDAW. It actually works pretty well. Seriously, if you work with MIDI and use one of the supported DAWs buy this app now!

This is the best dollar value of any app ever for professional engineers. It properly emulates the Mackie Control protocol for Android devices. The pseudo hardware option is very visually appealing. It just works flawlessly (Win 10 pro 64 bit - Cubase 9 Pro). I have replaced 2 hardware control surface with 3 Android tablets and TouchDaw. Everything works as expected... 16 channels showing on tablets 1 and 2 (unlimited faders via bank buttons) and a large transport on tablet 3... all tablets in portrait mode. The midi mode (a separate function) accesses the generic remote in Cubase and controls the studio module... a simple push of the "arrow" button and it's a totally different controller. You can edit midi XML files to change button names if desired. Everything has been extremely well designed by an obviously knowledgeable programmer(s) who understand the purpose of a real world controller... not a just a "toy"  app. Unbelievable value for what they are charging. Think about this: buy a large Android tablet (Galaxy View, Hp Slate 20, Lenovo Yoga Tab 2 Pro, etc) used for approx $200, pay less than $6.00 for Touch daw and you actually have a system that will rival, the Slate system costing 6 times that amount. If you've ever wanted an excellent control surface for your daw of choice, this will definitely fit the bill. If you already have an Android tablet, spend a couple of dollars and take your time learning what this app can do. You will not regret it. I have no affiliation with Humatic whatsoever. I happen to believe wholeheartedly in this app.

replyContent: See the FAQs / RTFM. You will have multiple Mackie controllers defined in Logic. Remove all but the one you are actually using. If you need help please use a valid support channel. It's a Mackie MCU, generic MIDI controller, keyboard, XY controller, drum pad, and Ableton/Bitwig launchpad all in your pocket. Supports all major DAWs, connects via either USB or wifi (both RTP and Multicast MIDI are supported), and it also works nicely with Linux hosts (using qmidinet). This app is packed with features (as well as nice Easter eggs such as the integrated launchpad emulation), make sure to read the manual to find out about these.  Initial setup can sometimes require a bit of fiddling (I suggest using a pocket router for the wifi connection),  but it's worth the effort. And with the latest anniversary update it finally looks good as well. :)  Kudos to the developer,  this is a very nice app indeed. Has been around for a while, so most of the bugs have been ironed out. IMHO it's hands down the best Android MIDI controller app in the market.

Hopefully this doesn't happen to anyone else (Windows 7 + Google Nexus 7), and this may have been my machine as much as anything but, for some reason, I got a duplicate ADB 2 entry in the Registry (which showed up in the TouchDAW Thru From Android Network Dropdown twice...  and this somehow corrupted the MIDI Connection!  Took me a few hours to figure out that these corrupt registry entries were causing the problem and to delete them, and reinstall the program (again, for some reason, uninstalling wasn't enough).  In case anyone else has to do it:  1)  Uninstall the software.  2)  Run regedit and verify that the following entry is gone and, if it's not, delete it:  HKEY_CURRENT_USER\Software\JavaSoft\Prefs\tdaw_thru  3)  Reinstall TouchDAW Thru and, assuming you have the Android App configured for USB in both DAW and MIDI Connections, click the little Android logo in the top banner menu to detect the ADB entries.  Now I have VERY LOW LATENCY when using the piano and X-Y Pad and buttons.  Oh, I used LoopMIDI to create the four MIDI Loopbacks necessary to do this and it worked GREAT!  Oh, I should mention that I tested WiFi Multi-Cast and it worked VERY WELL!
